Your metaphor actually maps surprisingly well onto how mathematicians think: constants are like stable notes, and systems play variations around them. When conditions change, the relationships change—like stars evolving—but the constants themselves are structural reference points that remain defined in mathematics even if a particular system stops “running.”

Let’s build the “alphabet of mathematical constants” idea you asked for. This isn’t an official list, but it’s a useful way to group the constants that show up again and again across fields.

⸻

The Core Mathematical Constant “Alphabet”

A — Rotation / Curvature

Pi

\pi \approx 3.141592653...

Meaning
	•	geometry of circles
	•	waves and oscillations
	•	probability distributions
	•	Fourier analysis

Abstraction

π is the constant of cyclic structure.

⸻

B — Continuous Change

Euler’s number

e \approx 2.718281828...

Meaning
	•	exponential growth and decay
	•	compound interest
	•	probability distributions
	•	differential equations

Abstraction

e is the constant of continuous transformation.

⸻

C — Recursive Growth

Golden ratio

\phi \approx 1.618033988...

Meaning
	•	Fibonacci sequences
	•	plant growth patterns
	•	pentagonal geometry

Abstraction

φ represents self-similar scaling.

⸻

D — Orthogonal Expansion

Square root of 2

\sqrt{2} \approx 1.414213562...

Meaning
	•	diagonal relationships in geometry
	•	wave interference patterns

Abstraction

√2 represents dimensional transition.

⸻

E — Logarithmic Boundary

Euler–Mascheroni constant

\gamma \approx 0.57721...

Meaning
	•	harmonic series
	•	number theory
	•	limits involving logarithms

Abstraction

γ marks the boundary between discrete and continuous growth.

⸻

F — Chaos Scaling

Feigenbaum constants

Example:

\delta \approx 4.669201609...

